  <h1 id="top">Probability Distributions</h1>
  <p>Seven distributions that appear across every GATE DA paper. Plug the right PMF or PDF into the E[X] and Var(X) machinery from Module 1.3 — then read off mean and variance directly from the table.</p>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 1: DISCRETE DISTRIBUTIONS ═══ -->
<h2 id="discrete">Discrete Distributions</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  A discrete RV takes countably many values, each with a positive probability mass. GATE DA tests identification, PMF evaluation, and mean/variance recall — rarely asks you to derive from scratch.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Bernoulli(p)</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$P(X=1)=p, \quad P(X=0)=1-p$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X]=p$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)=p(1-p)$</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:4px 0 0;">Trick: $(2X-1)^2 = 1$ always (2026 Q44)</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Binomial(n, p)</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$P(X=k) = \binom&#123;n&#125;&#123;k&#125; p^k (1-p)^&#123;n-k&#125;$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X]=np$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)=np(1-p)$</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:4px 0 0;">Sum of $n$ i.i.d. Bernoulli(p). With replacement = Binomial.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Geometric(p) — trials until first success</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$P(X=k) = (1-p)^&#123;k-1&#125; p, \quad k=1,2,\ldots$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X]=1/p$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)=(1-p)/p^2$</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:4px 0 0;">Memoryless: $P(X>m+n \mid X>m) = P(X>n)$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Poisson(λ) — rare events per interval</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$P(X=k) = \frac&#123;e^&#123;-\lambda&#125;\lambda^k&#125;&#123;k!&#125;, \quad k=0,1,2,\ldots$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X]=\lambda$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)=\lambda$ &nbsp;(mean = variance!)</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:4px 0 0;">Additive: $\text&#123;Pois&#125;(\lambda_1)+\text&#123;Pois&#125;(\lambda_2)=\text&#123;Pois&#125;(\lambda_1+\lambda_2)$</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--insight">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">Binomial = sum of n Bernoulli → why np and np(1-p)</span>
    $X = X_1 + X_2 + \cdots + X_n$ where each $X_i \sim \text&#123;Bernoulli&#125;(p)$. By linearity: $E[X] = nE[X_i] = np$. By independence: $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = n\,\text&#123;Var&#125;(X_i) = np(1-p)$.
  </div>
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">Binomial variance is $np(1-p)$, NOT $np$</span>
    $np$ is the mean. GATE regularly tests whether you confuse the two. Also: Poisson mean = variance = $\lambda$ — if mean ≠ variance it is NOT Poisson.
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 2: CONTINUOUS DISTRIBUTIONS ═══ -->
<h2 id="continuous">Continuous Distributions</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Continuous RVs have PDFs (densities). Each is fully covered in Module 1.5; know the key formulas cold for GATE MCQs.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Uniform(a, b)</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$f(x) = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;b-a&#125; \quad \text&#123;for&#125;\; a \le x \le b$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X] = (a+b)/2$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = (b-a)^2/12$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Normal(μ, σ)</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$f(x) = \frac&#123;1&#125;&#123;\sigma\sqrt&#123;2\pi&#125;&#125;\exp\!\!\left(-\frac&#123;(x-\mu)^2&#125;&#123;2\sigma^2&#125;\right)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X] = \mu$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = \sigma^2$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; Symmetric about $\mu$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Exponential(λ)</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$f(x) = \lambda e^&#123;-\lambda x&#125;, \quad x \ge 0$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$E[X] = 1/\lambda$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = 1/\lambda^2$ &nbsp;·&nbsp; Memoryless</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Normal — 68/95/99.7 rule</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$P(\mu - k\sigma \le X \le \mu + k\sigma)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">$k=1$: 68.3% &nbsp;·&nbsp; $k=2$: 95.4% &nbsp;·&nbsp; $k=3$: 99.7%</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:4px 0 0;">Standardise: $Z = (X-\mu)/\sigma \sim N(0,1)$</p>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ THEORY 3: APPROXIMATIONS ═══ -->
<h2 id="approx">Key Approximations</h2>
<p style="font-size:15px;color:var(--gd-text-1);margin-bottom:16px;line-height:1.6;">
  Two approximations appear almost every year. Recognition — seeing which form applies — is the full skill GATE rewards.
</p>

<div class="rules-grid">
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Poisson limit of Binomial</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Binom&#125;(n,p) \approx \text&#123;Poisson&#125;(np)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Use when: $n$ large, $p$ small, $np = \lambda$ moderate. Avoids huge factorials. (2026 Q45)</p>
  </div>
  <div class="rule-card">
    <div class="rule-card__label">Normal approximation (CLT)</div>
    <div class="gd-formula">$$\text&#123;Binom&#125;(n,p) \approx N\!\left(np,\, np(1-p)\right)$$</div>
    <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin:8px 0 0;">Use when: $np \ge 5$ and $n(1-p) \ge 5$. Standardise, then read $\varphi$. (2025 Q40)</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-insights">
  <div class="gd-insight gd-insight--warn">
    <span class="gd-insight__title">Without replacement ≠ Binomial</span>
    Binomial needs independence between trials. Sampling without replacement changes $p$ each draw — that's hypergeometric, not binomial. "With replacement" → $p$ stays constant → Binomial is correct. (2025 Q61)
  </div>
</div>

