<!-- ═══ WORKED EXAMPLES ═══ -->
<h2 id="examples">Worked Examples</h2>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 1 · Binomial — PMF, mean, variance</span>
    <p>A biased coin with $P(\text&#123;head&#125;) = 0.4$ is tossed 10 times. Find $P(\text&#123;exactly 3 heads&#125;)$, $E[X]$, and $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p>$X \sim \text&#123;Binomial&#125;(10,\, 0.4)$ — 10 fixed independent trials, $p=0.4$.</p>
    <p><strong>PMF:</strong> $P(X=3) = \binom&#123;10&#125;&#123;3&#125;(0.4)^3(0.6)^7 = 120 \times 0.064 \times 0.0280 \approx 0.215$.</p>
    <p><strong>Mean:</strong> $E[X] = np = 10(0.4) = 4$.</p>
    <p><strong>Variance:</strong> $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = np(1-p) = 10(0.4)(0.6) = 2.4$.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">P(X=3) ≈ 0.215 · E[X] = 4 · Var(X) = 2.4</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 2 · Poisson — PMF and "at least one"</span>
    <p>Calls arrive at an average rate of 3 per minute. Find $P(\text&#123;exactly 2 calls&#125;)$, $P(\text&#123;at least 1 call&#125;)$, and state $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X)$.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p>$X \sim \text&#123;Poisson&#125;(\lambda = 3)$ — rate gives the distribution directly.</p>
    <p><strong>Exactly 2:</strong> $P(X=2) = e^&#123;-3&#125; \cdot 3^2 / 2! = 4.5\,e^&#123;-3&#125; \approx 0.224$.</p>
    <p><strong>At least 1</strong> (complement): $P(X \ge 1) = 1 - P(X=0) = 1 - e^&#123;-3&#125; \approx 0.950$.</p>
    <p><strong>Variance:</strong> $\text&#123;Var&#125;(X) = \lambda = 3$ — equal to the mean, the Poisson signature.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">P(X=2) ≈ 0.224 · P(X≥1) ≈ 0.950 · Var = 3</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 3 · GATE 2025 Q61 — binomial mean from with-replacement draws (NAT)</span>
    <p>A bag has 5 white and 10 black balls. $n$ balls are drawn one at a time <strong>with replacement</strong>. $S_n$ = number of black balls drawn. Find $E[S_&#123;100&#125;]$ to one decimal.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Identify the distribution:</strong> each draw is independent (with replacement), $P(\text&#123;black&#125;) = 10/15 = 2/3$ is constant → Bernoulli(2/3) per draw.</p>
    <p><strong>$n = 100$ draws:</strong> $S_&#123;100&#125; \sim \text&#123;Binomial&#125;(100,\; 2/3)$.</p>
    <p><strong>Mean:</strong> $E[S_&#123;100&#125;] = np = 100 \times 2/3 = 200/3 \approx 66.7$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin-top:6px;">Without replacement: $p$ changes each draw → not binomial. With replacement: $p$ is constant → binomial.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Answer: 66.7</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="gd-example">
  <div class="gd-example__q">
    <span class="gd-example__num">Example 4 · GATE 2026 Q45 — Poisson PMF hidden in a limit (MCQ)</span>
    <p>$L = \lim_&#123;n\to\infty&#125; \sum_&#123;k=0&#125;^n e^&#123;-n&#125; n^k / k!$. Find $L$.<br>
    (A) 0.5 &nbsp;&nbsp; (B) 1.0 &nbsp;&nbsp; (C) 0 &nbsp;&nbsp; (D) $e^&#123;-1&#125;$</p>
  </div>
  <div class="gd-example__body">
    <p><strong>Recognise the PMF:</strong> each term $e^&#123;-n&#125; n^k / k!$ is $P(\text&#123;Poisson&#125;(\lambda=n) = k)$.</p>
    <p><strong>The sum is the CDF:</strong> $\sum_&#123;k=0&#125;^n P(\text&#123;Pois&#125;(n)=k) = P(\text&#123;Pois&#125;(n) \le n)$, i.e. the Poisson CDF evaluated at its own mean $n$.</p>
    <p><strong>Use the CLT:</strong> for large $\lambda=n$, $\text&#123;Pois&#125;(n) \approx N(n, n)$. So $P(X \le n) \to P(Z \le 0) = 0.5$.</p>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--gd-text-2);margin-top:6px;">The recognition step — spotting a Poisson PMF inside the sum — is the entire question.</p>
    <div class="gd-example__ans">Answer: (A) 0.5</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ═══ GATE ANGLE ═══ -->
<div class="gd-gate-box">
  <div class="gd-gate-box__title">GATE DA Angle</div>
  <p><strong>Memorise the mean/variance table cold:</strong> Bernoulli($p$), Binomial($np$, $np(1-p)$), Poisson($\lambda$, $\lambda$), Geometric($1/p$), Uniform($(a+b)/2$, $(b-a)^2/12$), Exponential($1/\lambda$, $1/\lambda^2$).</p>
  <p><strong>Binomial trap:</strong> variance = $np(1-p)$, not $np$. Mean = variance only for Poisson. Questions test these every year.</p>
  <p><strong>Poisson recognition:</strong> if you see $e^&#123;-\lambda&#125;\lambda^k/k!$ inside a sum or limit, that's a Poisson CDF. Evaluating it at the mean gives 0.5 (CLT symmetry). (2026 Q45)</p>
  <p><strong>With replacement → Binomial:</strong> "with replacement" keeps $p$ constant → Bernoulli per trial → Binomial for $n$ trials. Without replacement → not Binomial. (2025 Q61)</p>
  <p><strong>Normal approximation (CLT):</strong> Binomial$(n,p) \approx N(np, np(1-p))$ for large $n$. Standardise: $Z = (X-np)/\sqrt&#123;np(1-p)&#125;$. Then read $\varphi$. (2025 Q40)</p>
</div>

